Introduction (1/5)

Dissolved inorganic carbon (DIC)

Left figure from Friedlingstein et al., (2022)

DIC = HCO3- + CO32- + H2CO3 + CO2 (aq)

> 200 μmol/kg DIC gradient

Not uniform

Source of data: GLODAPv2

3 pumps acting against DIC mixing

\[\begin{gather*} pCO_{2}^{water~parcel} = \frac{[CO_{2}]}{K_{0}} \\ K_{0} \approx f(T) \end{gather*}\]

Cold DIC-enriched waters dive to depth

\[\begin{gather*} Ca^{2+} + 2HCO_{3}^{-} \rightleftharpoons CaCO_{3} + CO_{2} + H_{2}O \end{gather*}\]

Precipitation (DICsurf↘) vs. dissolution (DICdeep↗)

\[\begin{gather*} CO_{2} + H_{2}O \rightarrow CH_{2}O + O_{2} \end{gather*}\]

Photosynthesis (DICsurf↘) vs. respiration (DIC ↗)

Take-home message #1

  • Classifying plankton with constraints is challenging
  • Imbalanced dataset
    • Detritus are abundant (80%) and highly diverse
    • Living objects are rare
  • Room for improvement
    • 20/40 classes in the model
    • New features (e.g. texture)
    • Deal differently with detritus

Take-home message #2

  • OST and UVP6 are well correlated, especially at 1000 m
  • Preliminary results (1 year of data)
    • New method for jump detection
    • Guidi (2008) < Labrador Sea < Iversen (2010) ?
  • Need to investigate more
    • 3 parking depths — attenuation measurements
    • Environmental conditions (BGC variables)
    • Particle backscattering
    • Nature of particles (embedded classification)

CONVERSE (4/5)

CONtinuous VErtical SEquestration approach to carbon storage

BCP and its export pathways

POC (all) and DOC (mixing)

Gravitational settling or injection

Mixing + VMP merge back with BGP

Sequestration can occur at any depth

Continuous vs. fixed sequestration depth (e.g. 1000 m)

 BCP = BGP + VMP + Mixing pumps transport Forg

 Forg respired to CO2 (Fremin) or sedimented

Respiratory CO2 = biogenic DIC (DICbio)

 DICbio in the ocean for \(\geq\) 100 years = sequestered (Fseq)

 Carbon flux vs. carbon inventory → Pg C year-1

Ricour et al., (2023)

How can we compute Fseq ?

f100 — fraction of a water parcel at a given location and depth that will remain in the ocean for \(\geq\) 100 years

 OCIM model (Siegel et al., 2021)

f100 (avg) (530 m) = 0.3
 f100 (avg) (> 1000 m) = 0.87

Fseq = f100 x Fremin

7 CONVERSE versions to compute Fremin

Take-home message #3

  • Sequestration of DICbio not only in deep waters
  • Using a fixed sequestration depth underestimate Fseq(BCP)
    • CONVERSE Fseq(BCP) = 2-3 > Fseq(POC, 1000 m)
    • CONVERSE Fseq(BCP) = 3-6 > Fseq(POC, 2000 m)
  • VMP and Mixing pumps are important contributors to Fseq(BCP)
    • 21-34%
  • CONVERSE could be applied for the evaluation of mCDR strategies
